						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">To implement the selectable mirroring you'd have to steal one of the banking bits, so no, you can't make an AOROM-512 using a 4-bit register ('161 chip). You'd either need a second '161 or replace it with a larger register, which means different instructions.</div><br />What &quot;different instructions&quot; would be needed to write to a '377 vs. a '161? Color Dreams uses a '377, and the only difference between it and GNROM (which uses a '161) is the nibble swapping (and the mapping of PRG A18-A17 to control the CIC stun).</div>

